In case Exception is mentioned in the throws clause of method you may try
something like this

try
{
    method with input that causes the expected Exception to be thrown.
    assert(false);
}
catch (ExpectedException e)
{
assert(true);
}


in case the the exception thrown is not mentioned either in throws clause or
the documentation,  it should be treated as a bug/bad programming.
It does not matter whether the exception is system level or user defined.

Hope it helps,

Sachin
  -----Original Message-----
  From: G Ramasubramani [mailto:grama@...]
  Sent: Tuesday, December 19, 2000 1:45 PM
  To: junit@egroups.com
  Subject: [junit] Exception Handling Question




        Hi,


                In case I have a method which throws an exception on a
particular input, what would be the best way to write a test case which
shall succeed in case the exception is thrown?

                I thought of using something like


                try {

                        object.method();
               catch(ExpectedExceptionName e) {

                        assert(&quot;expected message&quot;, e.getMessage());

                }


                In this case however, it is a user defined exception and
hence I know what message to expect. What would be a proper course of action
in case it is a system level exception?


                I searched the archives, but could not find any mention of
this.

        thanks,
        Rama



